n Buddhism\nBULLET::::- Bodhiruci, patriarch of the Dilun () school\nBULLET::::- Batuo, founding abbot and patriarch of the Shaolin Monastery\nBULLET::::- Buddhaghosa, Theravadin commentator\nBULLET::::- Buddhapālita, early expositor of the Prasaṅgika branch of the Madhyamaka school\nBULLET::::- Chandragomin, renowned grammarian\nBULLET::::- Candrakīrti, considered the greatest exponent of Prasaṅgika\nBULLET::::- Dharmakirti, famed logician, author of the \"Seven Treatises\"; student of Dignāga's student, Īśvārasēna; said to have debated famed Hindu scholar Adi Shankara\nBULLET::::- Dignāga, famed logician\nBULLET::::- Garab Dorje, Indian founder of Dzogchen (Great Perfection) tradition\nBULLET::::- Kamalaśīla (8th century), author of important texts on meditation\nBULLET::::- Luipa, one of the eighty-four tantric Mahasiddhas\nBULLET::::- Nagarjuna, founder of the Madhyamaka school, widely considered the most important Mahayana philosopher (with Asanga)\nBULLET::::- Nadapada (Tib. \"Naropa\"), Tilopa's primary disciple, teacher of Marpa the Translator and Khungpo Nyaljor\nBULLET::::- Padmasambhava (Tib. \"Guru Rinpoche\"), Indian founder of Tibetan Buddhism\nBULLET::::- Saraha, famed mahasiddha, forefather of the Kagyu lineage\nBULLET::::- Śāntarakṣita, abbot of Nalanda, founder of the Yogacara who helped Padmasambhava establish Buddhism in Tibet\nBULLET::::- Shantideva (8th century), author of the \"Bodhisattvacaryāvatāra\"\nBULLET::::- Tilopa, recipient of four separate transmissions from Nagarjuna, Nagpopa, Luipa, and Khandro Kalpa Zangmo; Naropa's teacher\nBULLET::::- Vasubandhu, author of the \"Abhidharmakōśa\" and various Yogacara treatises; these may or may not be the same person\n\nBULLET::::- Dharmaraksita (3rd century BCE), Greek Buddhist missionary sent by emperor Ashoka, and a teacher of the monk Nagasena\nBULLET::::- Mahadharmaraksita (2nd century BCE), Greek Buddhist master during the time of Menander\nBULLET::::- Nāgasena (2nd century BCE), Buddhist s